deck_description: Did very well on many local tournaments with this bad boy, the main strategy is to spam your Xyz monsters and avoid any kind of field swep (cof cof nibiru cof).  Some of the usual combos I made were:  1- Pollux/Algeidi + any lvl4 = congrats, you have the most repeated R4 Xyz play of this deck  2- Pollux + Sheratan = Normal summon Pollux, then Sheratan. search for Caduceus, special summon it, search start chart with it. end with an R4 Xyz summon + Almiraj using Sheratan + Draw 1 if summoned a constellar Xyz mosnter with Star chart  3- Algeidi/Pollux/Caduceus + Kaus = normal summon Pollux/Algeidi or special summon Caduceus, then bring Kaus to the field. Activate it twice so you get 2 lvl 5 materials for your Pleiades. With Caduceus you can get Star chart an draw 1.  4- Galaxy soldier + discard material = easy CDI  Use Siat and Sombre for recovery/play-starts and that's pretty much it. Twinkle can be used very easely with 1 constellar in GY to make Pleiades, so dont be shy to search it with the Pollux+Sheratan combo. Didn't use Cradle on most of the matches but when i did, it saved the game.

deck_excerpt: A fun, Ritual good stuff deck.
deck_description: Hi, it's me again, Grayewick the Fusion strategy enjoyer, back with something different. This time, it's Impcantation Dogmatika, with Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon as its main boss monster (despite having 4 others). I've been having a lot of fun with this deck for a while so I decided to share it with y'all. A few questions you might have: • "What's with the messed up Extra Deck?" - for none other than Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries, of course! The only thing you'll gonna be using here are the two Elder Entity N'tss, Psy-Framelord Omega, the three Shaddoll Fusion monsters, and Nephthys, the Sacred Flame. Sure, floodgating your opponent with El Shaddoll Winda is nice and all, but there's nothing more fun than having your opponent stare at five gigantic Ritual Monsters under There Can Be Only One and Skill Drain. • "Nadir Servant at the Side?" - Yeah, it kinda gets redundant with Preparation of Rites, BUT, you can always fix that post siding. Strengths: • It's a pretty straightforward deck. All you gotta do is summon a big Ritual monster you wanna use then boost it with White Exalted of Dogmatika upon her Ritual Summon (just make sure you target the correct ones). • A lot of monsters with innate protection, like Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon,  Drytron Meteonis Draconids, and Archfiend's Awakening and interruptions in the form of Cyber Angel Vrash, Nekroz of Trishula, and Megalith Bethor. •  It isn't reliant to the Extra Deck to make plays. • It's fun to play! Weaknesses: • It can brick. (Unsurprisingly) • No innate back row removal, except for Nekroz of Trishula's effect. More tech options: • Pot of Prosperity/Pot of Extravagance for draw power • You can substitute some of your beat sticks with more control/stun oriented Ritual monsters like Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord and Magician of Black Chaos MAX, or an additional removal with Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys. Just be careful with the potential type overlaps for the purposes of There Can Be Only One.

deck_excerpt: Use dinosaurs to either search out Ultimate Conductor Tyranno and summon it with its effect or use double evolution pill to special summon it from the
deck_description: Use dinosaurs to either search out Ultimate Conductor Tyranno and summon it with its effect or use Double Evolution Pill to special summon it from the deck!  The dinosaur archetype got a new card in the ocg called Uradora of Fate. What that card does is: Pay 1000 lp to target 1 of your monsters and it (until the end of your opponents next turn) gains 1000 attack and when it destroys a monster by battle, reveal the bottom card of your deck to put either on top or on the bottom of your deck, if the card was a dinosaur, dragon, sea serpent, or wyrm monster, draw 1 card and gain 1000 lp for every 1000 attack the card has.  The reason that this card is so broken, is that Ultimate Conductor Tyranno can attack multiple times per turn and can beat over almost anything that it attacks so it will activate the effect multiple times to potentially draw a ton of cards and gain a ton of lp.

deck_excerpt: Dragon grave recursion / fusion monster deck.
deck_description: Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon, Back to the Front, Monster Reborn, Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon, Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon are all here to play cards from graveyards, and Odd-Eyes Advance Dragon and Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon can also hit things.  Albion the Shrouded, Fallen of Albaz, and the "Branded" set of cards allow us to play that archetype, as well as providing most of our fusion monsters and fusion support.  Dogmatika Punishment is great for both destroying things, and putting reanimation targets into the grave.  Dragon Ravine is great for grave filler, and Waking the Dragon's just for fun as much as anything else.  The Dark -- Hex-Sealed Fusion is also great for fusions.  Galactic Spiral Dragon and Nebula Dragon are both decent fillers, while Keeper of the Shrine is there just in case I ever actually have to properly tribute summon something.  Into the extra deck we have: the Branded friends, Albion, Brigrand, and Titaniklad, which work with Fallen of Albaz, have some not-bad abilities, and are beefy enough reanimation targets.  Starving Venom Fusion Dragon is an alternate for the three above, as Dark's a pretty common attribute at my table, and he's not bad either, despite easy requirements.  Starving Venemy Dragon's a pet card, but it's also decent, and weakens opponents over time if they can't get rid of it and/or have a grave-combo-heavy deck.  Beelze and Beelzeus are strictly grave fodder/reanimation targets. Wouldn't be too hard to build into, I just don't care to. Once they're out they're hard to get rid of anyways.

deck_excerpt: Pendulum Magicians with Crystron Halqifibrax engine
deck_description: This deck seeks to build a board of negates and pops when going first or break the opponents board with nondestruction removal effects when going second. Playing magician pendulum monster and tuning magician lets us go into a halqifibrax combo with one card without using pendulum summons which you can save as a second wave. Harmonizing Magician can summon the other half of a synchro summon or go into a halqifibrax combo. The deck is very consistent being mostly card search effects and plays through most disruption well if you know how to pilot it.

It's just for casual play this Deck is one of my favorite archetypes of Yu-Gi-Oh! although the Pendulum is already a dead summoning method whoever uses this deck may enjoy it and alter it as you guys like wish.

(disclaimer) this deck is the same as the last time Odd-Eyes only with some changed cards since I lost some in a fire that happened recently in my house and I don't know how to delete the Decks here
Play cards

The goal of this deck is to get Ultimate Conductor Tyranno out as fast as possible, while using other monsters in the deck's toolbox to protect it and negate any possible plays by the opponent. Use the "Scrap" monsters to get Synchro monsters. Take advantage of the "Giant Rex" floating effect, allowing for quick rank 4 plays. This is an alternative version of the Dinosaur deck that does not include the "Destiny HERO" engine, for those who do not want to use it. If cost is a constraint, one can use the PSY-Frame engine to replace some other hand traps in the deck (Note that a level 3 tuner must be run at all times if you opt-out of Ash). The most potent combo in this deck involves either a Turn 1 play with "Lost World", or Turn 2 play with only "Scrap Raptor".
  • Activate "Lost World"
  • Summon "Scrap Raptor" and destroy him using his own effect, adding "Scrap Chimera" to the hand
  • Normal Summon "Scrap Chimera" and use its effect to summon "Scrap Raptor" from the GY
  • Link into "Scrap Wyvern", use his effect to Special Summon "Scrap Raptor", then destroy "Scrap Raptor" and the "Jurraegg Token" using that same effect.
  • Use the effect of "Lost World" to destroy a Baby Dinosaur or Overtex Qoatlus in the deck instead. Use their effects accordingly.
  • Use the other effect "Scrap Wyvern" to special Summon "Scrap Golem" from the deck.
  • Use "Scrap Golem" to Special Summon "Scrap Raptor" from the GY
  • Link into "Crystron Halqifibrax" and Special Summon "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring"
  • Synchro Summon "Borreload Savage Dragon" and equip "Scrap Wyvern" to it from the GY

deck_excerpt: The second iteration of my previous Branded Albaz deck.
deck_description: Hi, it's me again, Grayewick the Fusion strategy enjoyer, back with my favorite Fusion archetype so far aside from Invoked and Shaddolls, Branded Albaz. This time splashing the Buster Blader package in a 60-card deck, pretty hefty but surprisingly consistent. My previous Branded Albaz deck list already have more than enough Dragon hate, it won't hurt for us to add even more. Not much significant change(s) in terms of the Branded Albaz ratios, only in the Extra Deck where I've decided to cut some more generic Fusion monsters to test other possible options (I am actually heavily considering Mysterion the Dragon Crown just because there are a lot of lines that allows you to make it with ease). Also, one thing I forgot mentioning in my previous deck list is that Magicians' Souls speeds up the deck significantly, not only because it draws you cards (which actually works well by discarding your Branded Condemnation or Branded Opening) but it also sends Dark Magician from the deck to the GY. You could always cut Destiny HERO - Dynatag and other Destiny HERO monster to make some space for it. Keeping it short and simple: Branded Fusion, Magicians' Souls, and Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman is a guaranteed Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman with Buster lock during your opponent's turn, either Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon (recommended if you opened Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous) or Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, and an additional 2 interruptions in the form of Branded Exile, mainly depending on your discards, which are made even better with drawing the "bricks" (Dark Magician, the Destiny HERO monsters, etc.) Side deck is always debatable, but I still do highly suggest Kaijus and outs that immediately address the board (Lightning Storm, Evenly Matched, etc.) than hand traps and floodgates. Note: I really tried making it as compact as possible, but 47-50 cards is the lowest I could get it to work without sacrificing consistency and options.

deck_excerpt: A pretty fun Fusion Summoning centered strategy.
deck_description: Hi, I'm Grayewick. I mostly play Fusion decks and I've decided to share my Branded Albaz deck list. I've been play testing and building this deck since it first got released in Dawn of Majesty, from splashing it with Darklords to making it work with Valkyries with Condemned Witch, and I think this is by far the best iteration of the deck that I've been building. A few questions you might have: • "Why run Despian Comedy?" - I'm actually surprised as to why not a lot of people run this card, considering the fact that it helps you dodge targeting effects like Infinite Impermanence and Effect Veiler. • "Why run 3 Branded Condemnation unlike most lists?" - It's a searchable Solemn Warning that also helps you recur your "Branded" Spells/Traps from your GY, which are either Screams of the Branded or Branded Exile as your main targets. A recyclable and searchable Super Polymerization is always great for a Fusion deck. • "4 Destiny HERO monsters and a Dark Magician?" - Unlike most Fusion decks that run DPE/Dragoon, these five monsters aren't really bricks, since all of them are DARK monsters, and there are hands that you'd be glad that you've drawn at least 1 Destiny HERO monster and/or Dark Magician, since there are combo lines that allows you to bring out both two of either Dragoon, DPE, and/or a Dynatag boosted Dystopia. • "No Prosperity/Handtraps/Crossout?" - Maybe it's just me, but I don't think running Prosperity in a deck with an already tight enough Extra Deck space is a good idea. If you feel like doing it, sure. It just isn't my cup of tea. If you wanna run hand traps, I suggest only those with LIGHT/DARK Attributes, for obvious reasons but then, you'd much rather run Kaijus of said Attributes/Santa Claws and cards that immediately address threats than trying to generate card advantage (which this deck already doesn't have much problem doing anyway).  Strengths: • It's a bit toolbox-y (as per most Fusion decks nowadays), but variety and flexibility is always a welcome trait especially for Fusion decks. • It breaks monster heavy boards with ease, and with the addition of Abyssal Dragon Alba Renatus, breaking an entire Dragon Link board has never been easier. • Much like other meta Fusion decks in the past, it can grind just as hard as them. It's a resource focused deck, and even with the help of Lubellion, the Searing Dragon, you'd still wanna be cautious. • Can easily play around Droll & Lock bird and most hand traps, and despite being able to swarm easily, getting hit by a Nibiru isn't really as punishing. Weaknesses: • Does not have an innate answer to back row, although that's what your side deck is for. • It does brick at certain occasions, though it can easily be remedied by having at least 1 LIGHT/DARK monster in either field, usually. • Mirror matches can be REALLY tough and grindy so as per usual, be mindful of your resources. • Floodgates, as per usual. Some other neat Fusion monster/Fusion engine choices for your choosing: • You can never go wrong with Invoked in any Fusion strategy. • A Buster Blader engine with ratios of your liking. Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman is a crazy card. • If you're not a fan of Despian Comedy, you could always substitute it with either a The Light - Hex-Sealed Fusion or Qadshaddoll Keios for El Shaddoll Winda. • Dark Cavalry or Dark Paladin aren't bad ideas either, considering that you have four Warrior-type monsters (five, if you're also using a Buster Blader engine.) Both are additional negations and are decent beat sticks, one of which pierces. • More semi-generic Super Polymerization targets like Despian Quaeritis, Despian Proskenion, Mysterion the Dragon Crown, etc.   Closing thoughts: Invoked Dogmatika and Dragon Link/Dragonmaid are the most fun match ups you can have, and "Konami pls ban Verte" KEKW

deck_name: Red Dragon Archfiend with Evil Eye
deck_excerpt: Summone crimson resonator, summon serziel watcher of the evil eye and combo off to big dragons and evil eye disruptions.
deck_description: The only really good combo in this deck requires crimson resonator and serziel, watcher of the evil eye, so a lot of the deck is just cards to search them and extenders. The deck really lacked consistency and I had to add couple of pot of desires even though I like using the extra deck as a toolbox and I feel like the pot banishes too much of it. The deck just really wasn't consistent when I tested it without the pots. But I feel like the deck maintains more cards in hand than my edge imp variant of the deck, but edge imp engine is maybe a better at recovery due to edge imp scissor. The biggest problem of the deck is probably that it is very weak to disruption. So going second is usually hard against combo and control decks, and going first requires the use use of crossout designators and caleld by the grave. The other problem is that the recovery is quite weak for non-tuner monsters. Red rising dragon can revive tuners etc but you really have to get another serziel to your hand or chaos ruler the chaotic magical dragon to your graveyard to recover from board wipes. Often this is not needed however since the goal is to just go into a mean disruption board. Overall I really like how this turned out. It is fairly consistent and red super nova dragon is just a boss. https://youtu.be/w1nHL-Ey6Gw

deck_excerpt: Probably the closest thing to a competitive Starry Night deck as of right now. Fun to play in a casual setting.
deck_description:
I. Deck Pros and Cons Pros
  • Slightly more versatile with use of the extra deck
  • Very high search power
  • Can lock the board down when going first
Cons
  • Fragile fragile fragile
  • Will almost never pull off any OTKs
  • Struggles going second
  • Needs setup for most card negation and destruction
  • Continuous spell and trap reliant, weak to backrow removal
II. Going Second If you have the choice of going first, always go first because of the amount of traps and setup you need. If you think you'll be going second after a round, you could remove cards such as Summon Limit , Honest , and Barrier Statue of the Heavens . Dark Ruler No More and Evenly Matched help you be able to be able to search and destroy comfortably without being interrupted. Artifact Lancea is also a good card to side in as it can be used by Starry Night Ceremony to search for your dragon. Other options for the side deck include Nibiru, the Primal Being , Artifact Scythe , and Artifact Sanctum .

deck_excerpt: Just some Fun With Icejades and Ursarctics
deck_description: So, the main plan is to have Radiation, do your Ursarctic combos and draw until you can get all necessary cards to lock down your opponent. Because of this we play a lot of two ofs. deck_excerpt: finally an Orcust Deck that does not lose to handtraps on it's normal summon
deck_description:
I've been using Orcust for 2 years and keep losing to handtraps on my normal summon. so i build this deck with the mindset that my opponent will always ash or imperm the trigger effect of Scrap Recycler or Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight. Yes, you need to draw specifically a starter and an extender, but at least you'll still be able to play through those handtraps with these extender. I'm also using some Sky Striker card as a pseudo called by the grave to dodges handtraps on the activation of Scrap Wyvern or 'Rusty Bardiche'. So the way you do these line is for example: (Scenario)
  1. you summon Scrap Recycler and activates it's effect to send a machine monster from your deck to the GY, and let say your opponent ash/imperm your 'Scrap Recycler'. so then you activate Cyberdark Claw searching Cyberdark Realm which then search your additional normal summon Cyberdark Chimera. Then with these 2 you make Scrap Wyvern. With the 'Cyberdark' cards, you will an extender and also a free pop with Scrap Wyvern's effect saving you an important card that normally you got to destroy or if you want to preserve your Scrap Wyvern. and then from there you just go ahead and do the full combo and pray to lord jesus god Cimoooooooo that your opponent doesn't have anymore interaction
  2. somehow you draw your World Wand/your Machina Citadel alongside Scrap Recycler. These are not considered to be a brick, cuz with Scrap Recycler you will then send your Machina Fortress, which then you can summon by sending either the World Wand/Machina Citadel. and with Machina Citadel in grave, your Scrap Wyvern are basically immune to Ash Blossom cuz you can chainblock it's effect.
  3. The Girsu line are basically the same as the scrap line, if you draw an extender with girsu, you won't be able to end on an Apoloussa, but you'll at least end on Rusty Bardiche + I:P + 2 Fog Blade + Ding in grave. so it is potentially 5 interruption which is not bad.
Keep in mind, that this build of the deck are not perfect and can still be improved. i just really really hate losing to handtrap that much. oh also, this deck hard loses to spells and traps that interact with your board (example: Lightning Storm and Evenly Match) cuz the end board only deals with monster effect with no spell/trap negation.

Use counter trap cards to disrupt your opponent's plays and gain extra effects from your fairy monsters on the field that gain effects when a counter trap is activated. This deck was seemingly forgotten about over time and it makes me kind of sad. It has some strong synergy with sanctuary on the sky which can never be understated.

You use the brave token stuff as an easy negate, free bodies ladder into verte, and the equip spell to bounce problem cards back to the hand. The eldlich stuff goes around the brave token restrictions, so I thought it would be a decent strategy to add into it. Some of the synergies here is if you have phoenix enforcer you can pop an eldland to get more advantage or the equip spell while you control a brave token to get it back. Overall I'm a pretty bad deck builder and a better version of this decklist is definitely out there but this has been pretty good.

deck_excerpt: An almost complete personal deck for winning against NPC's in Legacy of the Duelist: Link Evolution, just about everytime. "FTK" more than 9 times out
deck_description: Add Makyura to your hand with Painful Choice or Pot of Duality (or just draw it), then discard it with Dark World Dealings or Graceful Charity, after that use Painful Choice to thin out the deck (preferably by having another Painful Choice as one of the 5 cards, since the AI seems to always choose Painful Choice when you go with 5 Spell Cards, unless Chicken Game is one of the cards, then the AI seems to choose that instead.)  Also keep a Magical Mallet in hand at all times if you can, so that you can shuffle the Exodia pieces you've likely aquired back into the deck (in case you end up with something that might have you discard an Exodia piece) and draw new cards to likely extend the play unless you get really unlucky. (I am currently testing to swap out one Magical Mallet for a Dark Factory of Mass Production, to render this less of a problem, or to not completely screw you over if the opponent carries an annoying hand trap in their starting hand or something.)  Notes:  I'm not completely sure running 3x Dark World Dealings is the best idea with the discard effect. (Though it is more of a niche "This could go wrong in very specific situations" thing and it does help with discarding Makyura the Destructor now that I'm using a RML instead of Armageddon Knight.)  I switched out the Armageddon Knight for Royal Magical Library, as I already have plenty of ways to get Makyura to the graveyard, and RML helps extend plays those few times the "Heart of the cards" is not with me, heh.  Im wondering which out of Foolish Burial and Reinforcement of the Army would actually be the most consistent and complimentary. (Probably Foolish Burial considering I went for a RML instead of an Armageddon Knight.)  Also, I'm trying to minimize the amount of Trap cards, while still not rendering Makyuras effect completely moot, and Reckless Greed in this case works really well with Graceful Charity when activated from the hand as a chain, as you'll draw two extra cards before having to discard, which also makes it less likely to have things go kaputt.

deck_excerpt: Kaijus take opponent's beatsticks away, and Yosenjus get your Kaijus back. Back row traps help for your protection.
deck_description: Pretty simple deck mechanic here. Take away opponent's monsters with Kaijus, and use the Yosenjus to get your Kaiju back (Yosenju 1) or beat over it with an extra deck monster. Yosenjus come back to hand after normal summon, so it's a good idea to have back row protection and interruptions. There are a bunch of different cards to use and it's pretty easy to stay on the cheaper side. I have two droplets hence why there are two in there, but you can easily replace those with anything else. You can also interchange the traps (most people wouldn't play SMF, but I like it for the return). Side deck is also very interchangeable of course for whatever the meta is, and I would even have some back row disruptors possibly in there (Harpie's FD, TT, etc).
